	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>All of this stuff is really good, the main point is rangers don't have obviously powerful stuff.&nbsp;&nbsp;What we do have are flexible abilities which are only as useful as you can make them.  I seem to end up playing the tank more often than not, and I have learned one very important lesson from this, root rocks!  Sure warriors and pally's can taunt and take the dmg, but what happens when that orc would rather beat on your caster instead of the tank?  Root him, inform the group that he is rooted and let the caster back off.  That gives the group anywhere from 4-10 secs to deal with the problem, which in a good group is more than enough time.  I was in highpass the other evening and for quite some time was the primary healer and secondary tank for the group.  We spent some four hours where no one was ever above half hitpoints or mana, I was never able to buff anyone (all mana was going for heals and roots), but nobody died and we were not driven like sheep to the zone, ever.  You can be a great group player as a ranger if you use your skills the max, educate your party on what you can and cannot do, and keep them informed of what you are doing.  You can't tank like a war, pally, or even sk, but you can use taunt to spread out the dmg so your prim tanks aren't totally wiped out and you can use your weak ass heals to keep the main healers from wasting mana between battles when they should be medding.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
